# PMOVES: Agents, Spells & Geometry

*A visual guide to a magical multi-agent AI system*

## PMOVES Architecture Overview

![][image1]  
*Illustration: The PMOVES architecture as a layered multi-agent system. Each component is like a character in a fantasy team, with arrows showing how they communicate and share knowledge.*

At its core, **PMOVES** is a team of specialized AI “agents,” each with a unique role, all coordinated by a central brain. Together they solve complex tasks by sharing data and skills. Key components include:

* **Agent Zero – The Orchestrator:** The “central brain” that makes top-level decisions and delegates tasks[\[1\]](file://file-KvyPf9XMVfpWHZvzP3CrW2#:~:text=The%20PMOVES%20system%20is%20envisioned,and%20can%20create%20subordinate%20agents). Agent Zero learns and even creates helper agents. Think of it as the wizard overseeing the whole guild.

* **Archon – The Librarian:** A knowledge wizard and agent builder[\[2\]](file://file-KvyPf9XMVfpWHZvzP3CrW2#:~:text=Supporting%20Agent%20Zero%20are%20the,MCP). Archon manages the system’s knowledge (crawling web pages, processing documents, extracting code examples) and can forge new agents for specific tasks. It’s like the librarian who knows every spellbook and can conjure new apprentices.

* **n8n – The Workflow Conductor:** An automation messenger that passes tasks around[\[3\]](file://file-KvyPf9XMVfpWHZvzP3CrW2#:~:text=extraction%2C%20with%20advanced%20RAG%20strategies,components%20via%20the%20Model%20Context). n8n ensures all agents and tools (like data pipelines) work in harmony, similar to a conductor coordinating an orchestra.

* **Hi-RAG – The Scholar:** A **Hierarchical Retrieval-Augmented Generator** for deep reasoning[\[4\]](file://file-KvyPf9XMVfpWHZvzP3CrW2#:~:text=Specialized%20AI%20,image%20and%20video%20generation). Hi-RAG organizes knowledge into layers (like chapters and pages) so the system can handle very detailed questions. Imagine a wise sage who recalls facts from layered scrolls to answer tough riddles.

* **LangExtract – The Decoder:** A specialized agent for extracting structured facts from text[\[5\]](file://file-KvyPf9XMVfpWHZvzP3CrW2#:~:text=reasoning%20on%20complex%2C%20multi,ComfyUI%20handles%20sophisticated%20content). LangExtract combs through raw text (documents, transcripts) and pulls out structured information (like people, dates, errors) with source references. It’s the code-breaker or scribe that turns jumbled text into clear entries.

* **ComfyUI – The Artisan:** A creative tool for generating images or videos from instructions[\[6\]](file://file-KvyPf9XMVfpWHZvzP3CrW2#:~:text=information%20from%20unstructured%20text%20documents,image%20and%20video%20generation). ComfyUI runs sophisticated **text-to-image** and visual workflows, much like an artist in the team who can paint visions described in words.

* **Supabase – The Grand Archive:** A unified database that stores the team’s knowledge and semantic embeddings[\[7\]](file://file-KvyPf9XMVfpWHZvzP3CrW2#:~:text=The%20Data%20%26%20Operational%20Backbones,are%20a). It’s like a magical library or vault where all insights, vectors, and facts are kept. Every agent can fetch data from here when needed.

* **Local Models – The Minds:** A collection of local AI models (Ollama, NVIDIA Nemo, etc.) providing brainpower to the agents[\[8\]](file://file-KvyPf9XMVfpWHZvzP3CrW2#:~:text=the%20entire%20PMOVES%20system%2C%20serving,privacy%20and%20efficient%20local%20processing). These are the spells and enchantments (large language model capabilities) that the agents use, kept local for privacy and speed.

* **Infrastructure – The Foundation:** Distributed computers and Docker containers run all these agents[\[9\]](file://file-KvyPf9XMVfpWHZvzP3CrW2#:~:text=All%20these%20components%20are%20deployed,deploying%20components%20across%20this%20infrastructure). This is the robust castle (network of machines) and the supporting magic circles (containers) that keep everything isolated yet connected.

All these components work together to make PMOVES a self-improving, autonomous system[\[10\]](file://file-KvyPf9XMVfpWHZvzP3CrW2#:~:text=The%20PMOVES%20,Below%20are%20several%20Mermaid). For example, Agent Zero can ask Archon to gather info, Archon uses LangExtract and Hi-RAG to analyze data, results go into Supabase, and Agent Zero then instructs ComfyUI to create a visual report – all orchestrated via n8n. The design is modular and layered for easy improvement: each agent can be upgraded or new ones added without rebuilding the whole system, much like a well-organized guild[\[11\]](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/architecture/ai-ml/guide/ai-agent-design-patterns#:~:text=When%20you%20use%20multiple%20AI,agent%20solutions)[\[12\]](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/architecture/ai-ml/guide/ai-agent-design-patterns#:~:text=,the%20complexity%20of%20these%20tasks).

## Agent Zero – Master Conductor of the Agents

**Role in the Story:** Agent Zero is the mastermind, akin to a grand wizard or conductor. It doesn’t specialize in one domain – instead, it knows which expert agent to call for each job. Agent Zero keeps the team coordinated and decides **“who does what and when.”**

**Powers & Spells:** Agent Zero’s primary “spell” is **delegation** – it assigns tasks to the right agents and combines their results. For example:

\# Spell: Delegate a knowledge-gathering task to Archon via n8n  
agent\_zero.delegate(task="Analyze latest news on climate", to="Archon")

In practice, Agent Zero uses the **Model Context Protocol (MCP)** hub (the n8n orchestrator) to hand off work and data between agents[\[13\]](file://file-KvyPf9XMVfpWHZvzP3CrW2#:~:text=build%20hierarchical%20indices%20and%20enable,based%20on%20the%20generated%20insights). It can spawn new agents if needed, adjusting the team on the fly. Because Agent Zero has access to all local AI models and the Supabase knowledge vault, it can also answer questions directly or power up other agents as needed[\[14\]](file://file-KvyPf9XMVfpWHZvzP3CrW2#:~:text=The%20Data%20%26%20Operational%20Backbones,privacy%20and%20efficient%20local%20processing)[\[15\]](file://file-KvyPf9XMVfpWHZvzP3CrW2#:~:text=FORM%3DCREATOR%60.%20,artifact%20sharing%20requires%20explicit%20approval).

**Young Learner Metaphor:** Imagine Agent Zero as the leader of a superhero team. When a mission comes in, Agent Zero figures out which hero’s powers are needed. Need to investigate something? It calls the Detective (Archon). Need creative art? It calls the Painter (ComfyUI). By wisely delegating, Agent Zero ensures the whole team works together smoothly. It’s like the quest master in a role-playing game, assigning each character their quest.

**Trivia & Design:** In the PMOVES codebase, Agent Zero is implemented to run as a service (agent-zero) with an MCP server[\[16\]](file://file-KvyPf9XMVfpWHZvzP3CrW2#:~:text=,%E2%80%94%20tunable%20weights%20for). Different *forms* or modes (named “POWERFULMOVES”, “RESEARCHER”, etc.) define Agent Zero’s temperament in decision-making[\[17\]](file://file-KvyPf9XMVfpWHZvzP3CrW2#:~:text=%60geometry.jump%60%2C%20%60knowledge.rag.query%60%2C%20%60knowledge.codebook.update%60%2C%20etc.%20,artifact%20sharing%20requires%20explicit%20approval). For instance, a “Researcher” form might make it more cautious and analytical. By tuning these settings, Agent Zero can evolve, which is why we call PMOVES *self-improving*. Agent Zero is always learning which agent to trust for what task – just like a good leader learning their team’s strengths.

## Archon – The Knowledge Librarian & Agent Forger

**Role in the Story:** Archon is like a wise librarian or a sorcerer’s archivist. It handles all knowledge management – collecting information, remembering where everything is, and even creating new mini-agents for special tasks. If PMOVES were a school of magic, Archon runs the library and lab.

**Powers & Spells:** Archon’s spells revolve around knowledge retrieval and agent creation. It can ingest documents, scrape websites, and distill information. A signature spell might be a **“RAG (Retrieval-Augmented Generation) query.”** In code, it could look like:

\# Spell: Query the knowledge base via hierarchical retrieval  
answer \= archon.knowledge.rag.query("What are key points from the finance report?")

This would send a question into Archon’s indexed knowledge. Behind the scenes, Archon uses **vector search** in Supabase and **Hi-RAG** to find relevant chunks of text, then an LLM to compose an answer[\[18\]](file://file-KvyPf9XMVfpWHZvzP3CrW2#:~:text=3,as%20well%20as%20orchestrating%20ComfyUI)[\[19\]](file://file-KvyPf9XMVfpWHZvzP3CrW2#:~:text=knowledge%20management%20system,based%20on%20the%20generated%20insights). The result comes with sources (so it’s like a fact with footnotes). Archon can also “forge” agents – for example, given a task like translating PDF content regularly, Archon can spawn a specialized translator agent. It’s as if Archon can write a spell scroll (an agent script) on the fly for a specific need.

**Young Learner Metaphor:** Think of Archon as a mix between a librarian and a potion-brewer. It knows where every piece of knowledge is stored (books on shelves, data in databases). If you ask a question, Archon fetches the right books and even summarizes them for you. And if you need a special tool that doesn’t exist, Archon can brew one (create a new agent). For example, if you needed to gather weather data daily, Archon could create a “WeatherFetcher” agent to do it automatically.

**Real Examples:** Archon performs smart web crawling and document parsing[\[2\]](file://file-KvyPf9XMVfpWHZvzP3CrW2#:~:text=Supporting%20Agent%20Zero%20are%20the,MCP). It can extract examples of code from documentation or track tasks. One special ability is managing a “codebook” of patterns – essentially updating a memory of how certain problems were solved before. This aligns with research on continuous learning and self-refinement in AI agents[\[11\]](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/architecture/ai-ml/guide/ai-agent-design-patterns#:~:text=When%20you%20use%20multiple%20AI,agent%20solutions). Archon’s knowledge management ensures PMOVES can recall past solutions and apply them to new problems (like a student who remembers last semester’s lessons).

**Spell Card Snippet:** Archon might use a **codebook update** spell after solving a new problem:

\# Spell: Update knowledge codebook with a new insight  
archon.knowledge.codebook.update(new\_finding, source="research\_paper.pdf")

This way, the next time any agent faces a similar issue, Archon has that past “finding” ready. Archon truly weaves the **web of knowledge** that all other agents rely on.

## Hi-RAG – The Deep Reasoning Sage

**Role in the Story:** Hi-RAG (Hierarchical Retrieval-Augmented Generation) is the “sage” of the system, specializing in deep, multi-step reasoning. When a question or task is complex – like reading a long book and answering nuanced questions – Hi-RAG steps in. It’s as if Hi-RAG builds a **tree of information**, from big ideas down to tiny facts, to reason through a problem.

**How It Works:** Traditional retrieval-augmented generation might grab a few relevant passages to answer a question. Hi-RAG goes further by organizing information in layers or a hierarchy[\[4\]](file://file-KvyPf9XMVfpWHZvzP3CrW2#:~:text=Specialized%20AI%20,image%20and%20video%20generation). For example, to answer a question about a novel, Hi-RAG might first retrieve chapter summaries, then drill down to paragraphs in those chapters for details. It ensures consistency and thoroughness by not jumping straight to a detail without context. This hierarchical approach helps overcome limitations of basic retrieval that might miss context or get confused on long texts[\[4\]](file://file-KvyPf9XMVfpWHZvzP3CrW2#:~:text=Specialized%20AI%20,image%20and%20video%20generation).

**Powers & Spells:** Hi-RAG’s “spell” is essentially **structured thinking**. While not directly invoked by user commands (it works behind Archon or Agent Zero), we can imagine its process like a spell. For instance:

\# Pseudo-spell: Hierarchically retrieve and answer  
outline \= hirag.build\_index(texts=large\_document)  
answer \= hirag.deep\_answer(query="What is the theme of this document?", index=outline)

First it **builds an index** (outline of key points and sections), then it **deep-answers** using that structure. This two-step magic ensures the answer isn’t a shallow guess. Archon or Agent Zero might call Hi-RAG internally when faced with a big knowledge question – so Hi-RAG is like the wise elder the others consult for counsel.

**Young Learner Metaphor:** If the PMOVES team were investigating a mystery, Hi-RAG is the detective who says: “Let’s break this problem down. First, gather the clues. Now group similar clues together. Now analyze each group in depth.” For a kid, imagine reading a big storybook: Hi-RAG would first read the chapter titles to understand the story structure, then read each chapter, then answer questions about the whole book. It ensures it sees the **forest AND the trees**.

**Academic Connection:** Hierarchical reasoning like Hi-RAG’s relates to research on **multistep retrieval and multi-hop QA** – where an AI finds intermediate facts before the final answer. By structuring knowledge, Hi-RAG is performing a form of *fractal thinking*: each topic branches into subtopics, which branch further, just like a fractal tree. This echoes advanced AI research that suggests organizing knowledge in a graph or tree can improve accuracy and interpretability[\[20\]](https://www.ultra-unlimited.com/blog/spectral-fractal-symbolic-intelligence#:~:text=,Wigner%20semicircle%20law)[\[21\]](https://www.ultra-unlimited.com/blog/spectral-fractal-symbolic-intelligence#:~:text=,similarity%20across%20scales). It’s also akin to how humans outline topics to understand them.

**Fun Fact:** Hi-RAG not only finds relevant info but can also weigh how *reliable* the sources are (e.g., preferring peer-reviewed papers to random blogs for a science question). This makes the system’s answers more trustworthy. In a way, Hi-RAG adds wisdom to the knowledge – not just facts, but which facts to trust.

## LangExtract – The Multilingual Code-Breaker

**Role in the Story:** LangExtract is the agent you call when you have raw text or media transcripts that need to be turned into structured data. It’s like a magical decoder ring for language. If Archon is the librarian storing knowledge, LangExtract prepares the books to go on the shelves by extracting structured nuggets from unstructured text.

**What It Does:** LangExtract can take a block of text (say a document, an error log, or a YouTube transcript) and output structured JSON with the important pieces[\[22\]](file://file-TZV4MCWgtaiHBW5mUiTZJ4#:~:text=Notes%20,field%20required). For example, it can read an IT error log and extract fields like service: X, error\_code: Y, timestamp: Z[\[22\]](file://file-TZV4MCWgtaiHBW5mUiTZJ4#:~:text=Notes%20,field%20required). Or it can read an article and pull out Q\&A pairs or key points. This structured information is then saved into Supabase or passed to Archon/Hi-RAG for indexing. Essentially, LangExtract translates human-language content into database-ready facts.

**Powers & Spells:** LangExtract’s spells are its API endpoints, which work like incantations:

* POST /extract/text – Give it raw text, and it will return a list of structured chunks (paragraphs, questions, etc.)[\[23\]](file://file-TZV4MCWgtaiHBW5mUiTZJ4#:~:text=Service%20,d%20langextract).

* POST /extract/xml – Give it XML data, it will parse and convert to structured text segments[\[23\]](file://file-TZV4MCWgtaiHBW5mUiTZJ4#:~:text=Service%20,d%20langextract).

* It even recognizes things like questions (by ? or \<q\> tags) and extracts special fields like errors and exceptions from logs[\[22\]](file://file-TZV4MCWgtaiHBW5mUiTZJ4#:~:text=Notes%20,field%20required).

In code form, using LangExtract might look like:

\# Spell: Extract structured data from a text document  
result \= requests.post(  
    url="http://langextract/extract/text",  
    json={ "text": long\_text, "doc\_id": "news1" }  
)  
structured\_chunks \= result.json()\["chunks"\]

After this spell, structured\_chunks might be a list like \[{section\_id: 1, kind: "title", text: "News Headline"}, {section\_id: 2, kind: "paragraph", text: "First paragraph..."}…\]. These chunks then get embedded and stored for search. It’s like turning a long story into a neatly labeled outline automatically.

**Young Learner Metaphor:** Imagine you have a messy room full of lego pieces and toys mixed together. LangExtract is like a robot that sorts everything into labeled bins: legos in one bin, toy cars in another, puzzle pieces in another. That way, later on, when you need a certain piece, you know exactly where to find it. For language, it means if we have a jumble of text, LangExtract sorts sentences into categories (titles, questions, errors, etc.) so other agents can easily use them.

**Behind the Scenes:** LangExtract can work in different modes – a simple rule-based mode for speed (splitting on punctuation, known XML tags) or an AI-powered mode using Google’s **Gemini** LLM for more nuanced extraction[\[24\]](file://file-TZV4MCWgtaiHBW5mUiTZJ4#:~:text=Providers%20%28local,for%20offline%20local%20use). If the fancy AI isn’t available or fails, it falls back to rules[\[25\]](file://file-TZV4MCWgtaiHBW5mUiTZJ4#:~:text=error%20extraction.%20,for%20offline%20local%20use). This design ensures reliability. It reflects research practices in information extraction where you combine deterministic rules with AI for the best of both worlds – speed and accuracy. Moreover, every extracted piece keeps a reference to its source (for traceability), aligning with the **principle of source-grounded AI**[\[26\]](file://file-TZV4MCWgtaiHBW5mUiTZJ4#:~:text=This%20service%20and%20scripts%20convert,ready%20for%20embedding%20and%20indexing) (always being able to say *where* a fact came from).

**Why It’s Important:** Without LangExtract, Archon and Hi-RAG would have to deal with giant walls of text. LangExtract preprocesses and condenses content, making the later retrieval much faster (since it can skip irrelevant bits). It supports cross-modal work too – transcripts from audio and video can be turned into text chunks for indexing, which means PMOVES can recall something said in a video just as easily as something from a PDF. It’s literally building the cross-modal bridge through text.

## ComfyUI – The Creative Illusionist

**Role in the Story:** ComfyUI is the creative engine of PMOVES – think of it as the system’s resident artist or illusionist. When the team needs to generate an image, visualize data, or even create a short video, ComfyUI steps up with generative magic. It uses advanced diffusion models and AI pipelines to turn ideas into visuals.

**Capabilities:** ComfyUI orchestrates complex *content creation workflows*[\[27\]](file://file-KvyPf9XMVfpWHZvzP3CrW2#:~:text=often%20powered%20by%20LLMs%20like,image%20and%20video%20generation). For example, given a prompt “a flying car over a city at sunset, painted in watercolor,” ComfyUI can produce that image. It can also chain multiple steps: generate an image, upload it to storage, notify the system, etc. This is achieved with a node-based UI for diffusion models, hence the name “UI.” In PMOVES, it’s integrated so that other agents can request images or other media.

**Powers & Spells:** ComfyUI’s spells often involve **graphical pipelines** and dataset magic. One of its special integrations in PMOVES is with a **MinIO** storage service (an S3-like system) for saving outputs[\[28\]](file://file-GkYVrsDrqMDN6q41ACLcNe#:~:text=COMFYUI_MINIO_PRESIGN,Microservice)[\[29\]](file://file-GkYVrsDrqMDN6q41ACLcNe#:~:text=presign%3A%20build%3A%20.%2Fservices%2Fpresign%20restart%3A%20unless,false). For instance, a typical workflow:

1. **Generate Image Spell:** ComfyUI invokes a Stable Diffusion model with a text prompt. (Imagine a spell scroll reading: *“Summon Image: \[prompt text\]”*).

2. **Upload Spell:** After generation, it uses a presigned URL (from MinIO) to upload the image to the “assets” bucket[\[30\]](file://file-GkYVrsDrqMDN6q41ACLcNe#:~:text=MINIO_ENDPOINT%3Dlocalhost%3A9000%20MINIO_ACCESS_KEY%3Dminioadmin%20MINIO_SECRET_KEY%3Dminioadmin%20MINIO_SECURE%3Dfalse%20AWS_DEFAULT_REGION%3Dus,ALLOWED_BUCKETS%3Dassets%2Coutputs%20PRESIGN_SHARED_SECRET%3Dchange_me).

3. **Callback/Webhook Spell:** It then calls back (webhook) to notify PMOVES that the image is ready[\[31\]](file://file-YPoxsXLR7rCuWw4VN3PDKG#:~:text=Minimal%20Graph%201,Completion%20Webhook).

An example snippet initiating an image generation might be:

\# Spell: Create an image from text using ComfyUI  
comfyui\_request \= {  
    "prompt": "A castle under the stars, in Van Gogh style",  
    "webhook\_url": "http://pmoves/notify\_when\_done"  
}  
requests.post("http://comfyui/generate", json=comfyui\_request)

*(This is illustrative; actual ComfyUI uses a graph of nodes to generate and then uses a webhook to callback when done, as configured in PMOVES[\[31\]](file://file-YPoxsXLR7rCuWw4VN3PDKG#:~:text=Minimal%20Graph%201,Completion%20Webhook).)*

**Young Learner Metaphor:** ComfyUI is like the art class of the AI school. If Agent Zero says “we need a picture of this idea,” ComfyUI will paint it. It’s the creative friend who can draw anything you imagine. And because it’s automated, it can do this in seconds\! For instance, if our system was reading a story to a child, ComfyUI could draw each scene of the story as it goes. It’s as if you have a magic paintbrush that instantly creates images from words.

**Integration Magic:** Under the hood, ComfyUI in PMOVES uses custom nodes to interface with the rest of the system[\[28\]](file://file-GkYVrsDrqMDN6q41ACLcNe#:~:text=COMFYUI_MINIO_PRESIGN,Microservice). The **presigned URL** trick means ComfyUI doesn’t need direct database access – it just uploads the file and PMOVES knows where to find it. This decoupling is a good software design: it keeps the “artist” focused on art, while others handle storage. It also ensures large image files don’t clog the message channels; they go straight to object storage. This design echoes principles in **multimodal AI systems** where different modalities (text, image) are handled by specialized modules that communicate through defined protocols[\[32\]](https://aclanthology.org/2022.findings-acl.187.pdf#:~:text=tasks%20like%20image,pre%02training%20with%20objective%20of%20image) (like how CLIP aligns image and text representations in a shared space to work together).

**Fun Use Case:** In one scenario, PMOVES might use ComfyUI to generate a graph or chart visualizing data analyzed by Hi-RAG. For example, after Hi-RAG finds trends in a financial report, ComfyUI could be prompted to generate a bar chart image of those trends. In the mythic narrative, that’s like the scholar (Hi-RAG) handing notes to the artist (ComfyUI) who then illustrates the findings for the king (the user).

## The Geometry Bus – Multimodal Spellcasting with Shapes

Up to this point, each agent had its own specialty. The **Geometry Bus (CHIT)** is what truly ties them all together into one magic system. It introduces a common “language” of shapes (constellations) that any agent can use to reference content across text, audio, video, and images[\[33\]](file://file-KvyPf9XMVfpWHZvzP3CrW2#:~:text=4,CHIT)[\[34\]](file://file-KvyPf9XMVfpWHZvzP3CrW2#:~:text=,to%20jump%20between%20modalities). This is where PMOVES turns into a **story of spells and portals** – using geometry to navigate knowledge.

**CHIT Geometry Packet (CGP):** The core of the Geometry Bus is the CGP format[\[34\]](file://file-KvyPf9XMVfpWHZvzP3CrW2#:~:text=,to%20jump%20between%20modalities). Think of a CGP as a “geometry spell scroll” – it contains constellations of points that refer to pieces of content. Each **constellation** has an **anchor** (a direction or vector) and a **spectrum** – essentially a signature of where related content lies[\[34\]](file://file-KvyPf9XMVfpWHZvzP3CrW2#:~:text=,to%20jump%20between%20modalities). The points in a constellation carry references into various modalities: video timestamps, document token positions, audio timings, etc.[\[35\]](file://file-KvyPf9XMVfpWHZvzP3CrW2#:~:text=,to%20jump%20between%20modalities). In simpler terms, one constellation could link a video moment, an audio clip, and a text passage that all relate to the same concept (like three witnesses describing the same event in different languages).

*Above: JSON example of a minimal CGP (geometry capsule) with one constellation and point. Here, “c.test.1” is a constellation anchor called “beat-aligned hook” with a spectrum array, and it has one point “p.test.1” pointing to a video (YouTube ID “yt123”) at time 12.5s with a certain confidence. This single shape links a concept (“chorus line”) to a specific video moment.*

In the JSON above, notice:  
\- The **spectrum**: \[0.05, 0.1, 0.2, 0.3, ...\] – eight numbers that sum to 1.0. This is a soft distribution indicating where the content lies along some abstract axis or timeline. In this case, the highest values (0.3 around bin 4\) might indicate the chorus is mostly in the middle of the song (if we imagine bins spanning the song’s duration).  
\- The **anchor summary**: “beat-aligned hook” – a human-friendly tag for the constellation’s meaning (the musical hook that aligns with the beat).  
\- The **point**: It specifies modality: "video", ref\_id: "yt123" (an identifier for a YouTube video), t\_start: 12.5 (start time), frame\_idx: 300, and even some text “chorus line” which could be a snippet of lyrics at that point. Essentially, this point says “at 12.5s into video yt123, there’s a chorus line relevant to this constellation.”

**Visualization of the Spectrum:** Each constellation’s spectrum is like a **fingerprint** or energy signature of the content’s distribution. For example, plotting the spectrum above yields:

![][image2]  
*Spectrum of the “beat-aligned hook” anchor: The tallest bar is bin 4 (value 0.3), showing the hook’s strongest presence, with smaller presence in earlier and later parts. The spectrum acts like a roadmap for* where *in the timeline the anchor’s content is concentrated.*

In kid terms, if the constellation is about a song’s chorus, the spectrum might show in which part of the song the chorus appears most. Here it peaks in the middle, tapering off at the end.

**Magic of Anchors:** Every constellation provides an **anchor vector** – think of it like a direction in a high-dimensional space pointing to that concept[\[34\]](file://file-KvyPf9XMVfpWHZvzP3CrW2#:~:text=,to%20jump%20between%20modalities). If two constellations have similar anchors, it means they’re related (their spectra would be similar too). These anchors allow the system to jump across different media by alignment. For example, an anchor might represent “cat” – with points that are images of cats, the word “cat” in text, and a meow sound in audio. The anchor ties them together conceptually. This idea is quite like the concept of a *joint multimodal embedding space* in AI research, where text, images, and audio that mean the same thing are mapped to nearby vectors[\[32\]](https://aclanthology.org/2022.findings-acl.187.pdf#:~:text=tasks%20like%20image,pre%02training%20with%20objective%20of%20image). In fact, OpenAI’s CLIP model is famous for doing exactly that with images and captions: it aligns them in a shared vector space[\[32\]](https://aclanthology.org/2022.findings-acl.187.pdf#:~:text=tasks%20like%20image,pre%02training%20with%20objective%20of%20image), enabling, say, an image of a dog and the word “dog” to have similar embeddings. PMOVES’ anchors generalize this to many modalities and fine-grained segments of content.

**Using Shapes as Spells:** Agents publish and listen to these geometry packets. For instance, when LangExtract processes a video transcript, it could emit constellations for each detected topic with points linking timestamps. When a user (or Agent Zero) wants to find something, instead of just doing keyword search, they can ask the **Geometry Bus**. That’s like saying *“show me the shape of concept X”*. Decoders can then retrieve content by geometry-only queries – finding points whose constellation anchors match the query vector, even without exact keywords[\[36\]](file://file-KvyPf9XMVfpWHZvzP3CrW2#:~:text=,and%20encrypt%20anchors%20when%20sharing). This is an advanced “magic” that lets the system do things like **jump between modalities**:

*“From any point, jump to the corresponding video frame, audio span, or text snippet.”*[\[37\]](file://file-KvyPf9XMVfpWHZvzP3CrW2#:~:text=Exploration%20UI%20,and%20encrypt%20anchors%20when%20sharing)

In practice, that means if you have a text quote, PMOVES can find where it was said in a video and jump there instantly, because they share a shape in the geometry bus. That’s like a teleportation spell between different worlds (text world, video world) using the shape as a portal\!

**Security and Sharing:** The CHIT system even has security features – anchors/constellations can be signed or encrypted so only those with the key can use them[\[38\]](file://file-KvyPf9XMVfpWHZvzP3CrW2#:~:text=,and%20encrypt%20anchors%20when%20sharing). Think of it as secret spells that only trusted allies can read. This is done with HMAC signatures and optional encryption of anchor data[\[38\]](file://file-KvyPf9XMVfpWHZvzP3CrW2#:~:text=,and%20encrypt%20anchors%20when%20sharing). It allows sharing a geometry capsule with someone else in a verifiable way – the receiver knows it’s authentic and unchanged.

**Academic Insights:** The use of geometry to unify modalities relates to concepts of **holographic memory** in cognitive science – where memory is distributed and content is retrieved by pattern similarity rather than exact address. In a holographic associative memory, information is stored in interference patterns and any part can retrieve the whole by resonance[\[39\]](https://philarchive.org/archive/FEROOI-2v1#:~:text=2,the%20principles%20of%20holographic%20cognition). Similarly, PMOVES’s anchors and spectra are like distributed patterns; you don’t look up an exact key, you throw a vector (pattern) and get back matching patterns (even if they’re different media). This “resonant retrieval” is echoed in the design – *meaning is not stored in one location, but emerges through similarity and interference of vectors*[\[39\]](https://philarchive.org/archive/FEROOI-2v1#:~:text=2,the%20principles%20of%20holographic%20cognition). The **spectrum bins** also hint at spectral decomposition – capturing the “frequency” components of content, which is reminiscent of how our brains might encode information in neural frequency patterns[\[20\]](https://www.ultra-unlimited.com/blog/spectral-fractal-symbolic-intelligence#:~:text=,Wigner%20semicircle%20law). Additionally, representing knowledge in a geometry that supports fast sub-100ms jumps between points[\[40\]](file://file-KvyPf9XMVfpWHZvzP3CrW2#:~:text=In,sub%E2%80%91100ms%20interactive%20scrubbing%2Fjumping%20between%20modalities) speaks to building an interactive experience where navigation is as smooth as a video game, which requires efficient vector search (often using advanced indexes like HNSW, which is a graph – interestingly, constellations and shape\_index in Supabase play a similar role[\[41\]](file://file-KvyPf9XMVfpWHZvzP3CrW2#:~:text=Recommended%20Supabase%20tables%20%28minimal%29%3A%20,modal%20lookup)[\[42\]](file://file-KvyPf9XMVfpWHZvzP3CrW2#:~:text=,modal%20lookup)).

In short, the Geometry Bus is what transforms PMOVES from a set of individual agents into a **multimodal, interconnected mind**. It’s the common tongue or the weave that binds all knowledge.

## Mythic Storytelling – Bouncing the First Shape

Let’s conclude with a bit of mythology. In the world of PMOVES, how did these capabilities awaken? It started with a single act: someone **“bounced a shape.”** This means the user (or developer) took a simple geometric constellation – a shape representing an idea – and sent it through the system. It was like casting a stone across a pond and watching the ripples connect every lily pad. This first geometry packet might have been as simple as the **c.test.1** example above, but it demonstrated the potential: all parts of the system reacted to it.

When the first shape was published on the Geometry Bus, Archon recorded it, Hi-RAG tried to decode and summarize it, ComfyUI could even visualize it (imagine plotting that constellation’s points on a canvas), and Agent Zero realized it could use this method to link agents together. The previously separate modes of text, audio, and vision were now **anchored** on a common map. The assistant (Agent Zero) and PMOVES as a whole found a new synergy – a shared geometric memory. It unlocked what we might call **holographic synergy**: the ability for the AI to jump between different forms of knowledge seamlessly, because they all shared an underlying representational structure.

In narrative terms, *a sorcerer discovered a geometry capsule that lets anyone jump between time and meaning*. Suddenly, the team could do things not possible before – like find exactly when in a video a certain idea was mentioned and then create an image of that idea, all in one flow. The geometry capsule (CGP) was that enchanted object. It encapsulated an anchor (direction of meaning) and points across realms (modalities). Tossing it into the “pool” of the Geometry Bus created ripples that every agent could sense and act on.

This “first shape” story parallels how big breakthroughs often happen in research: one unifying idea (here, geometric unification of data) triggers a cascade of innovation. It also resonates with academic explorations of **fractal structuring from anchors to endpoints** – basically building knowledge from coarse anchors down to fine details in a self-similar way[\[43\]](https://www.ultra-unlimited.com/blog/spectral-fractal-symbolic-intelligence#:~:text=Purpose%3A%20Analyze%20multiscale%20self,embedding%20in%20cognitive%20systems%20Functions)[\[44\]](https://www.ultra-unlimited.com/blog/spectral-fractal-symbolic-intelligence#:~:text=,neural%20graphs%20or%20linguistic%20structure). In PMOVES, a single anchor can lead you to multiple endpoints (points in text, video, etc.), and each endpoint can further lead to more details (e.g., jumping 5 seconds earlier in the video, or reading the surrounding paragraph in text). This creates a fractal-like exploration pattern: any point you jump to can itself be an anchor for deeper jumps. Such a system could resemble a *knowledge fractal*, where each answer leads to new questions in another modality, endlessly. Researchers in AI and cognitive science have suggested that intelligence may involve this kind of fractal, self-similar expansion of ideas across contexts[\[21\]](https://www.ultra-unlimited.com/blog/spectral-fractal-symbolic-intelligence#:~:text=,similarity%20across%20scales)[\[43\]](https://www.ultra-unlimited.com/blog/spectral-fractal-symbolic-intelligence#:~:text=Purpose%3A%20Analyze%20multiscale%20self,embedding%20in%20cognitive%20systems%20Functions). PMOVES provides a practical blueprint of that: anchors (ideas) connecting to points (instances) across the graph of modalities, enabling recursive exploration.

**Example of Synergy:** Suppose the user asks, “Tell me something interesting about Beethoven’s 5th Symphony.” Traditionally, one agent might just look up text about it. In PMOVES, here’s what could happen with the geometry-enabled synergy:

1. **Archon** fetches a Wikipedia article and some music theory documents about Beethoven’s 5th. LangExtract structures this text.

2. **Jellyfin YouTube Ingestion** (one of the workers) pulls a performance video of the symphony and runs analysis (audio analysis finds the famous “da-da-da-dum” motif timings, etc., possibly creating constellations for motifs)[\[45\]](file://file-KvyPf9XMVfpWHZvzP3CrW2#:~:text=PMOVES_ARC,manages%20and%20streams%20this%20content)[\[46\]](file://file-KvyPf9XMVfpWHZvzP3CrW2#:~:text=graphs).

3. Those constellations (shapes) are published. Now **Hi-RAG** has both the text data and the musical anchors. It notices through the Geometry Bus that a certain motif shape appears in both the sheet music (as a pattern of notes) and the audio (as a repeated sound pattern).

4. **Agent Zero**, via n8n, orchestrates ComfyUI to generate a visual: maybe a chart aligning the motif’s shape in audio vs notation.

5. Finally, Agent Zero gives the answer: “Beethoven’s 5th starts with a short-short-short-long motif (【audio clip】 at 0:00:05, see shape below) which appears in many parts of the symphony. It’s like a musical ‘word’ Beethoven uses. I’ve drawn its shape for you and where it occurs\!” And it could present an image of the waveform or musical notation via ComfyUI.

This rich answer was possible because the system could connect text, audio, and image through geometry. It’s the *synergy* that was unlocked by bouncing that first shape – showing all agents how to speak a common shape language.

**Citations & Connections:** This PMOVES approach stands on the shoulders of research in several domains. For instance, the idea of using anchor points to represent structure is similar to methods in computer vision and information retrieval, where centroids or anchors help align different feature spaces[\[47\]](https://arxiv.org/abs/2403.00648#:~:text=query%20and%20gallery%20models,Comprehensive%20experiments%20on)[\[48\]](https://arxiv.org/abs/2403.00648#:~:text=vectors%20in%20the%20quantizer%20serve,centroid%20vectors%20are%20considered%20as). The notion of rapid cross-modal jumping relates to interactive multimedia retrieval research, where systems let users click on a transcript and instantly see the corresponding video frame, requiring precise alignment of text and video timelines[\[37\]](file://file-KvyPf9XMVfpWHZvzP3CrW2#:~:text=Exploration%20UI%20,and%20encrypt%20anchors%20when%20sharing). And the overarching concept of a distributed memory resonates with Karl Pribram’s holographic brain theory[\[39\]](https://philarchive.org/archive/FEROOI-2v1#:~:text=2,the%20principles%20of%20holographic%20cognition) and Pentti Kanerva’s **Holographic Associative Memory**, where memory is distributed in a high-dimensional space and retrieval is pattern-based[\[49\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Holographic_associative_memory#:~:text=For%20holographic%20data%20storage%20%2C,The%20information)[\[50\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Holographic_associative_memory#:~:text=response%20memories%2C%20where%20information%20is,At%20the). In such a memory, “each part contains the whole” in some way[\[39\]](https://philarchive.org/archive/FEROOI-2v1#:~:text=2,the%20principles%20of%20holographic%20cognition) – similar to how each constellation anchor in PMOVES holds a summary (like “beat-aligned hook”) that can recreate the pieces (points) across modalities when decoded.

By grounding its architecture in these principles, PMOVES achieves a flexible, extensible intelligence system. It’s both **technically literate** (grounded in the latest AI techniques) and imbued with **playful wonder** – we described it in terms of wizards, spells, and magic shapes because, at its heart, it’s about turning the complex sorcery of AI into an intuitive, almost storytelling-friendly form. Each agent is like a character, each spell like a coded function, and each shape a portal. Together they form a **trading card set** of capabilities that work in concert – a modern kind of sorcery built on code, data, and geometry.
